<DocsLayout title="Button reference"><p class="eyebrow">Reference</p><h1>Button</h1><p class="lede">A framework-native button with Kumo variants, sizes, loading text, disabled behavior, and forwarded native attributes.</p>
<h2>Props</h2><div class="table-scroll" tabindex="0" role="region" aria-label="Button properties"><table><thead><tr><th>Prop</th><th>Type</th><th>Default</th><th>Behavior</th></tr></thead><tbody>
<tr><td><code>variant</code></td><td><code>primary | secondary | danger</code></td><td><code>primary</code></td><td>Visual intent.</td></tr><tr><td><code>size</code></td><td><code>small | medium | large</code></td><td><code>medium</code></td><td>Padding and text scale.</td></tr><tr><td><code>disabled</code></td><td><code>boolean</code></td><td><code>false</code></td><td>Native disabled state; handlers do not fire.</td></tr><tr><td><code>loading</code></td><td><code>boolean</code></td><td><code>false</code></td><td>Disables the control and announces loading text.</td></tr><tr><td><code>type</code></td><td><code>button | submit | reset</code></td><td><code>button</code></td><td>Native button type.</td></tr>
</tbody></table></div>
<h2>Events</h2><p>Use the framework’s native event syntax: <code>onclick</code> in Svelte, <code>@click</code> in Vue, and <code>onClick</code> in Solid.</p>
<h2>Accessibility</h2><ul><li>Renders a native <code>&lt;button&gt;</code>.</li><li>Has a minimum 44px control height.</li><li>Preserves native keyboard activation and disabled semantics.</li><li>Requires a meaningful accessible name from its child content.</li></ul>
<h2>Example</h2><pre><code>{`<Button variant="primary" onclick={() => count += 1}>
  Clicked {count}
</Button>
<Button disabled>Disabled</Button>`}</code></pre></DocsLayout><style>.eyebrow{margin:0 0 10px;color:#b45309;font-size:13px;font-weight:850;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:.09em}</style>
